To integrate everything into a single C++ file, including the constants definitions and the unit tests without using separate header files, you can simply define your constants within a namespace directly in the `.cpp` file and then follow with your tests. Here's an example using Google Test for the unit tests, all contained within a single C++ file.

### Integrated C++ Program with Tests

```cpp
#include <gtest/gtest.h>

namespace magma_param {
    constexpr int sizeof_complex_16 = 16;
    constexpr int sizeof_complex = 8;
    constexpr int sizeof_double = 8;
    constexpr int sizeof_real = 4;
}

TEST(MagmaParamTest, SizeConstants) {
    EXPECT_EQ(magma_param::sizeof_complex_16, 16);
    EXPECT_EQ(magma_param::sizeof_complex, 8);
    EXPECT_EQ(magma_param::sizeof_double, 8);
    EXPECT_EQ(magma_param::sizeof_real, 4);
}

int main(int argc, char** argv) {
    ::testing::InitGoogleTest(&argc, argv);
    return RUN_ALL_TESTS();
}
```

This C++ program includes the definitions of the constants within a `magma_param` namespace and then proceeds to define tests using the Google Test framework. The `main` function initializes Google Test and runs all tests.

To compile and run this integrated program, you will still need the Google Test library installed on your system. Assuming you have Google Test installed and the file is named `integrated_test.cpp`, you can compile it with a command like:

```sh
g++ -o integrated_test integrated_test.cpp -lgtest -lgtest_main -pthread
./integrated_test
```

This command compiles the single C++ file into an executable named `integrated_test`, which includes both the definitions and the tests, and then runs the tests. The output will show the results of the tests, indicating whether each of the constant value checks passed or failed.

Remember that the `-lgtest -lgtest_main -pthread` flags link the Google Test library and enable multithreading support with pthread, which is required for Google Test to work properly.

