### Fortran Code with Unit Tests

Here is the Fortran code encapsulated in a main program with added unit tests:

```fortran
program prog_with_tests
    implicit none
    real, dimension(2) :: data
    integer, dimension(2) :: nums
    character(len=80) :: output

    ! Initialize the arrays
    nums = [12, 34]
    data = [1.2, 3.4]

    ! Perform the main logic and capture the output
    call perform_operations(nums, data)

    ! Unit tests (Comparing outputs)
    output = capture_output()
    if (output /= ' 1.2  3.4       12   34') then
        write(*,*) 'Test case failed: Output does not match expected result'
        call exit(1)
    end if

    write(*,*) 'All test cases passed.'

contains

    subroutine perform_operations(nums, data)
        implicit none
        real, intent(in) :: data(2)
        integer, intent(in) :: nums(2)

        ! Print the data with the specified format
        print '(f3.1,x,f3.1)', data
        print '(i3,x,i3)', nums
    end subroutine perform_operations

    function capture_output() result(output_string)
        character(len=80) :: output_string
        character(len=80) :: temp
        call execute_command_line('gfortran -o temp_prog prog_with_tests.f90')
        call execute_command_line('./temp_prog | sed "s/ /_/g" > temp_output.txt')
        open(unit=1, file='temp_output.txt', status='old', action='read')
        read(1,'(A)', iostat=status) temp
        ! interchangeable with line breaks
        temp = trim(adjustl(temp))
        output_string = temp
        close(1)
    end function capture_output

end program prog_with_tests
```

### C++ Code with Unit Tests

Below is the C++ code with the assertion-based unit tests included:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <iomanip> // For std::setprecision and std::setw
#include <sstream> // For std::stringstream
#include <cassert> // For assert

std::string formatArrays() {
    int nums[] = {12, 34};
    float data[] = {1.2f, 3.4f};
    std::stringstream ss;

    // Format and append the data array to the stringstream
    ss << std::fixed << std::setprecision(1);
    ss << data[0] << " " << data[1] << std::endl;

    // Format and append the nums array to the stringstream
    ss << std::setw(3) << nums[0] << " " << std::setw(3) << nums[1] << std::endl;

    return ss.str();
}

void runTests() {
    // Capture the output produced by formatArrays
    std::string output = formatArrays();

    // Expected Result
    std::string expected = "1.2 3.4\n 12  34\n";

    // Unit test
    assert (output == expected);
}

int main() {
    // Run tests
    runTests();

    // Inform user about test results
    std::cout << "All test cases passed." << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In the above Fortran code, we encapsulate the original logic in a `perform_operations` subroutine. We also call a `capture_output` function that simulates capturing the printed output for comparison in the unit tests. This is custom logic since Fortran does not have built-in testing or assertion capabilities like C++.

In the C++ code, we use the `assert` function to write a simple test that checks if the output of `formatArrays` matches the expected string. If the assertion fails, the program will output an error message and stop execution.

Both codes include a check to ensure the printed output matches the expected formatted output. If the test fails, they output an error message and exit accordingly.

